      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As Bob Herbert warns (column, Aug. 21), Gov. George W. Bush should be careful about using the term ''class warfare'' against the Democrats; it might turn around and bite him.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As Bob Herbert warns (column, Aug. 21), Gov. George W. Bush should be careful about using the term ''class warfare'' against the Democrats; it might turn around and bite him.</p>
        <p>When the Republicans in Congress oppose an overdue increase in the minimum wage and vote to abolish an estate tax that falls mostly on the rich, while their presidential nominee proposes a huge tax cut that will allow mainly the rich to get richer, who is engaging in class warfare? The Republicans have evidently not learned from history. They are sowing the seeds of a political backlash.  PETER A. CORNING  Palo Alto, Calif., Aug. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
